Note: wc (word count) prints the number of lines, words, and bytes in files or input streams.
It is useful for measuring text size, counting items, and validating data.
Only basic and commonly useful examples are included here. The command has additional capabilities not covered in this section.

Count lines in a file

wc -l file.txt

Count words in a file

wc -w file.txt

Count bytes in a file

wc -c file.txt

Count lines, words, and bytes together

wc file.txt

Count lines from piped input

cat file.txt | wc -l

Count the total number of lines across multiple files

wc -l *.txt

Show only the total lines from multiple files

wc -l *.txt | tail -n 1

Count characters (useful for Unicode-aware systems with wc -m)

wc -m file.txt
